03:51.480 --> 04:03.620
There's a legendary UFO researcher named Dr. Roger Lear, who everybody likes to pay homage to, and I view you as kind of his living heir in many ways.

04:04.140 --> 04:06.220
Yeah, I guess that's about right these days.

04:06.380 --> 04:11.940
I mean, nobody else has taken up the research, and he taught me everything he knew.

04:11.940 --> 04:21.420
So I would very much like to continue the research when funding becomes available.

04:22.500 --> 04:26.400
It's crazy that funding should be completely available.

04:26.560 --> 04:28.140
This is like the most interesting stuff.

04:28.520 --> 04:34.380
So let's just establish for the audience, who is Dr. Roger Lear?

04:34.520 --> 04:37.660
He's known as this sort of alien implant doctor.

04:38.280 --> 04:39.920
What was his background?

04:40.200 --> 04:41.280
How did he get into this?

04:41.280 --> 04:44.820
Well, he was a podiatrist, and he was always interested in UFOs.

04:44.860 --> 04:48.700
He was the most knowledgeable ufologist I've ever met.

04:49.360 --> 04:59.840
And he was at a UFO conference once, and Daryl Sims tried to get him into an alien implant, and he thought the subject was ridiculous at first.

05:00.640 --> 05:05.540
Then he finally said one of his friends convinced him to take another look at it.

05:05.540 --> 05:18.620
So he said to Daryl, well, you know, get some of these people down here to my office, and we'll get them x-rayed and take the object out and see what it is.

05:18.960 --> 05:20.380
And so that's how the research started.

05:20.380 --> 05:27.800
And he ended up taking out 17 objects from 17 different people over about a 20-year period.

05:27.800 --> 05:32.320
We found the object, the first one, and we took it out.

05:32.880 --> 05:37.840
It looked like nothing that I had ever removed before in a way of a foreign body.

05:38.000 --> 05:46.920
And believe me, I had removed all sorts of things from even a hair to paper to metals of various kinds and so on.

05:46.920 --> 05:49.180
I never saw anything like this.

05:49.240 --> 06:00.320
It was a T-shaped affair that was wrapped in a very tight biological tissue, which was this really strange color and texture.

06:00.840 --> 06:04.780
And then we took a scalpel, and we wanted to see what was inside.

06:05.780 --> 06:07.360
That's the idea of the whole thing.

06:07.440 --> 06:11.800
And we were amazed to find that we couldn't cut through this biological tissue.

06:11.800 --> 06:16.500
It came back with absolutely no inflammatory response.

06:17.640 --> 06:26.040
Now, that really makes you want to scratch your head, because how do you get something into the human body and not have the body react to it?

06:26.120 --> 06:27.800
Well, that just doesn't happen.

06:28.780 --> 06:34.400
Maybe there's some weirded-out explanation that I didn't understand from one site.

06:34.400 --> 06:44.440
Maybe two sites, but three sites from two different people, that's just a little too much to handle.

06:44.660 --> 06:45.800
And where was he based?

06:46.360 --> 06:52.400
I found out that Dr. Lear was working in Thousand Oaks when I was working in Camarillo, California, only a few miles away.

06:52.400 --> 07:06.380
And I had a weird experience where I saw these giant raccoons in my backyard when I was at the house alone one night.

07:07.120 --> 07:14.640
And I fed the animals and observed them for some time, and they were about between 75 and 100 pounds, I'd estimate.

07:15.140 --> 07:17.140
I didn't even know raccoons got that big.

07:17.140 --> 07:28.300
And evidently, there were scout animals for the aliens, because I went to bed and woke up about 8 o'clock the next morning and had a bad stinging pain in my toe.

07:29.200 --> 07:33.520
And I had reason to believe it was some kind of an implant, and so I went to see Dr. Lear.

07:34.040 --> 07:39.560
And I don't think he believed me at first, but he gave me a prescription to get the toe x-rayed.

07:40.640 --> 07:45.640
And I knew we were going to see something on the x-ray, but when I did, that changed my life forever.

07:45.640 --> 07:48.020
It looked like a bent piece of wire on the x-ray.

07:49.260 --> 07:59.660
And I didn't remember getting any shrapnel in there or anything like that, so it was quite an experience.

07:59.820 --> 08:08.100
Then he got funding from Jaime Masson to remove it a few months later, and he didn't have anybody to analyze it.

08:08.100 --> 08:20.360
And so, where I was working at the time, I had access to a lot of analytical equipment, so I analyzed it for him, and it turned out to be a sophisticated nanotechnological device.

08:21.820 --> 08:24.080
Have you read my paper on that implant?

08:24.080 --> 08:26.900
I have not. Let's hear about it.

08:27.780 --> 08:41.040
Well, it turned out to have very skewed isotopic ratios and several elements that were in the metallic core, and to the extent that it looked like it probably came from another part of the galaxy, not just another planet.

08:42.660 --> 08:45.420
How can you know that from the isotope ratios?

08:45.420 --> 09:01.940
Well, because the isotope ratios are characteristic of elements from different places, and if they're off by more than a percent or so, that means it's not from Earth.

09:02.760 --> 09:04.740
These were off by up to like 30%.

09:04.740 --> 09:06.940
What were the elements, and what were the isotopes?

09:07.780 --> 09:16.800
The first one, I think it was boron and copper, and there were similar results from other implants I analyzed.

09:17.780 --> 09:34.260
And anyway, the structure of the device was a gray, hard-to-cut membrane, and below that, a layer of material that was similar to bone, like a biological hard part, like bone or mother of pearl.

09:34.260 --> 09:47.660
Then below that, a metallic core that made of meteoric iron with carbon nanotubes inside the metal, and nerve cells connected to the device.

09:48.860 --> 10:00.320
The pain in my toe got worse over a period of days and led to a lot of electric shock-type pain whenever I put any weight on the toe.

10:00.320 --> 10:05.260
And I think that was the nerve cells running in the device.

10:06.140 --> 10:12.920
These devices also produce no physiological reaction in the body, and that's unheard of.

10:13.000 --> 10:15.420
Foreign objects always produce a physiological response.

10:15.520 --> 10:16.740
So there's no immune response.

10:16.900 --> 10:17.940
No immune response, right.

10:18.340 --> 10:19.120
Really interesting.

10:19.120 --> 10:27.420
And could these elements and isotopes theoretically have been produced in some sort of centrifuge?

10:28.120 --> 10:35.520
You could, but in order to produce those exact ratios, it would probably cost millions of dollars and be very difficult to do.

10:35.680 --> 10:36.820
So the question is why?

10:37.260 --> 10:38.260
And why would anybody do that?

10:38.260 --> 10:39.440
Why would anybody do that?

10:39.520 --> 10:39.720
Yeah.

10:39.720 --> 10:46.680
Do you remember undergoing some sort of alien abduction experience prior to that being in your toe?

10:46.680 --> 10:53.780
I didn't remember it consciously, but I underwent regressive hypnosis and remembered aliens putting in the device, yeah.

10:54.060 --> 10:55.520
What was that experience like?

10:55.520 --> 11:06.320
Well, two small gray beings came into my room and woke me up and said, come outside.

11:06.700 --> 11:12.560
And I put on these steel-toed boots I had by the bed and went outside with them.

11:12.600 --> 11:18.400
And there was a UFO hovering at a very low altitude over the backyard over this avocado tree I had at the Fillmore house.

11:18.400 --> 11:28.780
And they indicated that I should stand below the center of the craft and took me up with a tractor beam.

11:29.380 --> 11:30.820
And Star Trek got it right, by the way.

11:30.880 --> 11:35.360
It's like a blue or greenish beam that lifts things, a gravity beam.

11:36.000 --> 11:43.860
And the center of the craft, it was about 50 feet in diameter, similar to Lazar's sport model, if you're familiar with that.

11:44.000 --> 11:44.320
Oh, yeah.

11:44.320 --> 11:54.480
And the center of the device or craft was an airlock that had human and alien spacesuits available.

11:54.880 --> 11:58.860
And there were four doors leading to the four quadrants of the craft.

11:59.220 --> 12:09.880
Then there was a habitation ring around the outside and a pilot station with two pilots and prepared to be thought controlled.

12:09.880 --> 12:13.820
They had their hands in a panel and on top of a panel.

12:14.320 --> 12:18.360
And screens where they were observing different things.

12:19.800 --> 12:26.900
And they took me around to the station at 90 degrees, so the pilot station.

12:27.100 --> 12:31.620
And there was a couch that slid out of the wall.

12:32.000 --> 12:35.140
And this guy indicated for me to lie down.

12:35.520 --> 12:38.740
And it was a taller gray.

12:38.740 --> 12:52.500
And he took out a device that looked like a black plastic handle with a piece of quarter-inch stainless steel tubing on it and touched it to my toe and pushed a button.

12:53.460 --> 12:55.620
And that must have put the implant in.

12:55.620 --> 13:03.160
And there were fiber optics going down the center of this piece of tubing.

13:03.600 --> 13:06.680
And I think that's what activates the device, UV light.

13:06.960 --> 13:11.480
And I think that's what accounts for these red marks you see on experiencers, too.

13:11.540 --> 13:13.920
I think they're mini sunburns from UV light.

13:14.920 --> 13:15.360
Interesting.

13:15.360 --> 13:17.260
And so, how long were you up there for?

13:19.140 --> 13:19.880
About an hour.

13:20.640 --> 13:25.440
They waited for a long time for orders, I think, before actually putting in the device.

13:25.560 --> 13:28.800
I think because they knew I'd start an investigation and they weren't sure they wanted that.

13:29.000 --> 13:31.380
Because a bunch of weird stuff had been happening previously.

13:34.020 --> 13:35.380
Where were you living at the time?

13:35.780 --> 13:36.700
Fillmore, California.

13:36.940 --> 13:37.560
Okay, Fillmore.

13:38.420 --> 13:40.520
And was this during that night?

13:40.900 --> 13:43.080
Yeah, it was a night about 3 in the morning.

13:43.280 --> 13:44.860
They usually come about 2 or 3 in the morning.

13:47.060 --> 13:53.500
And so, finally, after about, being up for about 45 minutes, I go, like, guys, you know, I'm tired.

13:53.640 --> 13:57.280
If you're not going to do anything, then let me go back to bed.

13:57.640 --> 13:59.960
So, they put the device in at that point.

14:00.100 --> 14:03.800
And that didn't take very long once they decided to make up their minds.

14:04.120 --> 14:05.960
Are you communicating telepathically with them?

14:05.980 --> 14:06.820
Yeah, telepathically.

14:07.080 --> 14:07.360
Okay.

14:07.560 --> 14:09.560
Do you see any symbols around the craft?

14:11.160 --> 14:14.200
Yeah, there were some symbols that looked like hieroglyphics.

14:14.640 --> 14:20.100
I'm labeling the instruments on the pilot station and on some of the walls.

14:20.880 --> 14:31.340
They had a, I believe they had a vector symbol, a blue vector symbol on the wall, a pretty big symbol.

14:31.340 --> 14:34.920
And it had two dots, circles below it.

14:34.920 --> 14:51.440
And their uniforms are usually cobalt blue and have either a snake with a snake over a triangle or three orange circles arranged in an equilateral triangle.

14:51.440 --> 15:01.020
And I'm led to believe that the three orange circles arranged in an equilateral triangle is the symbol of the gray alliance.

15:01.020 --> 15:04.840
The, the, the grays are not one species.

15:04.840 --> 15:16.220
There were like several, I believe seven different species of similar aliens that are bound by treaty and come within, come to us from planets within a hundred light years of here.

15:16.220 --> 15:17.860
Where, how are you getting that?

15:17.860 --> 15:20.060
Uh, they, I believe they told me.

15:20.060 --> 15:21.020
Oh, they told you that.

15:21.020 --> 15:21.120
Yeah.

15:21.700 --> 15:24.740
And, uh, what else did they tell you?

15:25.520 --> 15:30.820
Uh, a lot of stuff about physics and, um, propulsion, most of which I can't remember consciously.

15:31.140 --> 15:33.060
Do you remember anything about the physics and propulsion?

15:33.280 --> 15:33.880
Uh, yeah.

15:34.100 --> 15:34.320
Yeah.

15:34.420 --> 15:40.640
Um, they use a combination of, or several methods to create any gravity and they, they definitely have any gravity drives.

15:40.640 --> 15:45.380
And, um, they use, uh, like three different methods to create, um, anti-gravity.

15:45.480 --> 15:46.540
Do you remember the methods?

15:46.980 --> 15:47.340
Yeah.

15:47.440 --> 15:49.620
One of, one of those is a home polar generator.

15:49.920 --> 16:01.140
Um, if, if you take a disc, the basic home polar generator is, uh, a disc, uh, a metallic disc rotating, uh, in a perpendicular magnetic field.

16:01.140 --> 16:05.020
And it creates a voltage between the, uh, the center and the outside of the disc.

16:05.020 --> 16:15.680
And, um, the aliens use a version of that, uh, to create most of their lift where, um, they, uh, circulate, uh, molten metal around the outside of the craft.

16:15.680 --> 16:22.060
That's, uh, magnetic, uh, uh, from, uh, analyzing samples of the material that were dropped.

16:22.240 --> 16:26.600
I think it's usually a, uh, mixture of, um, iron and silicon.

16:27.120 --> 16:29.240
The silicon's probably in there lower the melting point.

16:29.240 --> 16:35.660
And, um, there's a strong magnetic field, um, between the top and bottom of the craft.

16:35.900 --> 16:48.080
That's why, uh, the, um, uh, that's why equipment like, uh, car electrical systems goes out when a UFO is near because of the very, very strong magnetic field.

16:48.080 --> 17:03.560
And, um, um, they also, um, use a method, um, called the Bifield-Brown effect to generate lift where, um, you rapidly charge a capacitor, um, and, and there's a thrust in the direction of the positive pole.

17:03.880 --> 17:13.980
Um, and the, uh, a lot of these things, the entire craft is a capacitor between the top and bottom, um, uh, the top and bottom, uh, of the craft are like plates of a capacitor.

17:14.500 --> 17:17.040
So they told you they used the Bifield-Brown effect, these aliens?

17:18.080 --> 17:18.480
Yeah.

17:18.800 --> 17:19.660
That's really interesting.

17:20.140 --> 17:32.240
And, um, uh, the, uh, according to Bob Lazar, they didn't, I don't remember him telling me this, but according to Bob Lazar, they also use element 115 sometimes to amplify the gravitational effect.

17:32.440 --> 17:32.740
Yeah.

17:33.420 --> 17:33.860
Yeah.

17:33.860 --> 17:34.460
That's amazing.

17:34.680 --> 17:36.440
I'm, uh, I'm obsessed with Townsend-Brown.

17:36.440 --> 17:39.580
So I, I, that gets me excited.

17:39.720 --> 17:46.960
The fact that there's some, you know, corroboration from an experiencer that, you know, maybe that, that is how the craft actually works.

17:46.960 --> 17:51.960
Many institutions and people have tried to either downplay or falsify Brown's experiments.

17:52.300 --> 17:58.220
For example, in 1990, the Air Force tested a Bifield-Brown experiment in a vacuum, but they

17:58.220 --> 18:02.620
only used 19 kilovolts instead of the megavoltage Brown was using.

18:02.620 --> 18:17.400
But in 1956, Jacques Corneon, a French Air Force officer and technical representative for one of France's largest aircraft companies, Sued West, facilitated Brown's experiments in a vacuum in the Montgolfier facility in Paris.

18:17.400 --> 18:20.440
The tests were very, very, very tricky.

18:21.280 --> 18:24.640
It was sensitive to so, so many things.

18:25.340 --> 18:27.580
In fact, finally it worked.

18:27.980 --> 18:30.060
So that was the positive result.

18:30.900 --> 18:31.980
Did they say anything else?

18:32.020 --> 18:34.720
So they're giving you all this insight into the, into the physics?

18:35.140 --> 18:39.120
Uh, they, they talked about time travel quite a bit, um, and the physics of that.

18:39.360 --> 18:40.160
What did they say?

18:40.160 --> 18:43.320
They said that, um, that they have time travel.

18:43.420 --> 18:55.840
They don't like to use it very much because, um, and especially don't like to do long jumps because you could, um, if you travel back in time too far, you could get back, you get on a different timeline and it would be difficult to get back to your own.

18:56.700 --> 18:58.060
Uh, that's the main reason.

18:58.060 --> 19:26.140
Um, there's, um, the many worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics is, um, is, uh, generally correct except that, um, uh, minor decisions, I'm not sure how the universe decides what's a minor decision and what's a major one, but, um, minor, uh, decisions in quantum mechanics, uh, where something happens on a subatomic scale, um, most of those, uh, just collapse on themselves and don't become a separate timeline.

19:26.140 --> 19:26.880
But some do.

19:27.280 --> 19:27.400
Hmm.

19:27.780 --> 19:31.320
So this is this idea that the wave function doesn't actually collapse.

19:31.340 --> 19:32.620
It sort of infinitely branches.

19:32.920 --> 19:33.020
Right.

19:33.020 --> 19:34.680
But you're saying that in certain cases.

19:35.200 --> 19:35.920
It's a combination.

19:36.220 --> 19:39.920
Some, some, most of them collapse, but some of them continue on and become a different timeline.

19:40.260 --> 19:41.160
Makes rough sense.

19:41.220 --> 19:41.660
That's interesting.

19:42.080 --> 19:42.260
Yeah.

19:42.260 --> 19:42.320
Yeah.

19:42.420 --> 19:45.580
And, and the, the, the, the ones that do continue on are as real as this one.

19:45.800 --> 19:46.160
Hmm.

19:46.460 --> 19:54.760
And, um, if you go back, uh, too far and then try to go forward again, there's a chance you might end up on one of those branch points.

19:55.100 --> 19:55.500
Yeah.

19:55.500 --> 19:58.580
Went across one of the branch points and end up on a different timeline.

19:58.580 --> 20:02.840
Did they connect the, you know, quote unquote, anti-gravity with the time travel?

20:03.020 --> 20:10.820
Because Byfield Brown effect and Townsend Brown himself was very interested in time travel because of their relationship between gravity and time and general relativity.

20:11.760 --> 20:16.700
Well, the way they move faster than light is that they, they use the anti-gravity drive to open up a wormhole.

20:16.700 --> 20:23.040
And, um, I'm not sure how they, um, they choose where the other opening of the wormhole is, but they, they can do that somehow.

20:23.040 --> 20:29.920
And then they'll go through it and, uh, go a few million kilometers before the wormhole collapses because wormholes are unstable.

20:29.920 --> 20:33.240
And, um, they can do the same thing with time.

20:33.320 --> 20:38.880
They just open up a wormhole in a different time where the, the, the opening is in a different time that they want to visit.

20:38.880 --> 20:49.220
And the other reason they don't like to use time travel too much is because, um, it's difficult to judge exactly when you're going to come out to the second like they like to do.

20:49.220 --> 21:01.000
Yeah. Well, that seems to be the case. And you have like Travis Walton dropped off near where he was picked up, but not, it's usually not like very precise and there's like sort of missing time involved.

21:01.400 --> 21:08.940
Yeah. Yeah. And Dr. in, um, Travis Walton's case, Dr. Lear thinks he would, or thought he was dead and they brought him back to life.

21:09.140 --> 21:11.600
Whoa. Why does Roger Lear think that?

21:11.600 --> 21:25.320
A lot of the people I talked to on this show, whistleblowers, intelligence insiders, people who've worked on classified programs, they all say the same thing when it comes to protecting your cyber security.

21:25.320 --> 21:30.920
They often comment on the fact that ordinary people basically have no privacy when they're online.

